    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>The Real Reason You're Still Sore on Day Three</h2>

    <p>Here's what most men are told: "You're sore because you're getting older. Recovery just takes longer after 40. That's normal." And they accept it — because it feels true, and because nobody has offered them a better explanation.</p>

    <p>Here's what's actually happening: exercise creates microscopic tears in muscle fibers. That's not damage to be avoided — it's the stimulus that drives adaptation and growth. The soreness you feel is the inflammatory response that follows, as your body dispatches repair resources to the damaged tissue. Under normal circumstances in a younger, well-fueled body, this process resolves in 24–48 hours.</p>

    <p>After 40, two things change. First, <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> means your muscles' repair machinery responds less efficiently to the signal to rebuild. Second — and this is the part most men never hear — if you're not eating enough protein, your body literally doesn't have the raw materials to complete the repair job on schedule. The construction crew shows up but there's no lumber. The job drags on.</p>

    <p>That 72–96 hour soreness that feels like aging? For most men, it's a protein deficit wearing an age costume.</p>

