    <!-- SECTION 2 — THE BIOLOGY -->
    <h2>The Biology of DOMS — What's Actually Happening</h2>

    <p>Delayed onset muscle soreness — DOMS — develops 12–48 hours after exercise because the inflammatory repair process takes time to get underway. The peak discomfort typically arrives 24–72 hours post-workout, not immediately after, which is why you often feel fine leaving the gym and wake up stiff the next morning.</p>

    <div class="science-strip">
      <h3>The Repair Process — Step by Step</h3>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>Step 1 — Micro-damage occurs during exercise.</strong> Eccentric movements (the lowering phase of any lift, running downhill, stair descents) create the most micro-tearing. This is normal and necessary — it's the stimulus that triggers adaptation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>Step 2 — Inflammation signals the repair crew.</strong> Within hours, inflammatory markers flood the damaged tissue. This is what creates the stiffness and tenderness. The inflammatory response is not the problem — it's the repair mechanism. The problem is when it lingers because the repair is slow.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>Step 3 — Amino acids rebuild the fiber.</strong> Protein from your diet is broken into amino acids, which are transported to the damaged muscle fibers to reconstruct the micro-tears. The speed of this step is directly proportional to the availability of amino acids — specifically leucine, which triggers muscle protein synthesis via the mTOR pathway.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>Step 4 — Inflammation resolves as repair completes.</strong> Once the fibers are rebuilt, the inflammatory signals dissipate and soreness clears. With adequate protein, this happens in 24–48 hours. With inadequate protein, the repair stalls, inflammation persists, and you're still sore on day three — or four.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

