    <!-- SECTION 3 — ANABOLIC RESISTANCE CONNECTION -->
    <h2>Why This Hits Harder After 40</h2>

    <p>Anabolic resistance — the age-related decline in your muscles' sensitivity to protein signals — is the multiplier that makes protein deficiency so costly after 40. At 28, your muscles respond to a moderate protein intake with a robust repair response. At 48, the same protein intake triggers a significantly weaker signal.</p>

    <p>This means two things for recovery:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>You need more total daily protein</strong> to generate the same repair response — research supports 1.2–1.6g per kilogram of bodyweight, compared to 0.8g/kg for younger adults.</li>
      <li><strong>Per-meal dosing matters more</strong> — your muscles need at least 30–40g of protein per meal to cross the leucine threshold that triggers muscle protein synthesis. A 15g lunch doesn't contribute meaningfully to repair, regardless of your daily total.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>The <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-pacing-strategy-men-over-40/">protein pacing research</a> is directly relevant here: men who distribute protein across 3–4 meals of 30g+ recover measurably faster than men who eat the same total unevenly. The repair machinery needs consistent amino acid availability throughout the day — not one large hit at dinner.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">The Compounding Problem</div>
      <p>When you're sore for 3+ days, you typically reduce workout frequency or intensity — which reduces the training stimulus that drives adaptation — which makes you more susceptible to soreness next time you train. The protein deficit creates a recovery cycle that makes training feel harder and less productive, reinforcing the false belief that your body "just can't handle it anymore." Fixing protein breaks the cycle.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 4 — THE POST-WORKOUT WINDOW -->
    <h2>The Post-Workout Window — When Protein Matters Most</h2>

    <p>Exercise dramatically increases muscle protein synthesis rates for 1–2 hours post-workout. During this window, your muscles are primed to absorb and use amino acids for repair at a significantly higher rate than at rest. Research from Dr. Stuart Phillips at McMaster University and others consistently shows that consuming 30–40g of protein within this window accelerates recovery and reduces the duration of DOMS.</p>

    <p>This isn't about taking a specific supplement. It's about having a protein-anchored meal or snack within two hours of finishing your workout. Greek yogurt and eggs. A chicken breast. Cottage cheese with a protein source alongside it. The source matters less than hitting the threshold.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>The post-workout meal is not optional for men over 40.</strong> At younger ages, the repair response is robust enough that timing matters less. After 40, anabolic resistance means the window is narrower and the dose requirement is higher. Missing the post-workout window on a regular basis is one of the primary reasons men over 40 feel like training "doesn't work" the way it used to. See <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/50g-protein-breakfast-men-over-40/">how to build a 40–50g meal</a> that covers this window effectively.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 5 — THE RECOVERY PROTOCOL -->
    <h2>The 3-Part Recovery Protocol</h2>

    <div class="protocol-grid">
      <div class="protocol-card">
