        <h4>Hit Your Daily Target — Every Day</h4>
        <p>Recovery happens over 24–48 hours, not just in the meal after a workout. Your muscles need amino acid availability throughout the full repair window. Consistently hitting 1.2g/kg daily is more important than any single meal timing strategy. Use the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-calculator-men-over-40/">protein calculator</a> to find your exact number.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="protocol-card">
        <div class="pc-icon">⚡</div>
        <h4>30–40g Within 2 Hours Post-Workout</h4>
        <p>Don't let the post-workout window close without a threshold-clearing protein dose. Greek yogurt, eggs, cottage cheese, a whey shake — anything that hits 30g+ within two hours of finishing. This is the single highest-leverage timing move for recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="protocol-card">
        <div class="pc-icon">🌙</div>
        <h4>Casein Before Bed on Training Days</h4>
        <p>Muscle repair continues overnight while you fast. Cottage cheese (25g of slow-digesting casein protein) before bed on training days provides a steady amino acid supply during the overnight repair window — directly reducing next-morning stiffness. See the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/whey-vs-casein-vs-collagen-men-over-40/">casein vs whey breakdown</a> for why this matters.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 6 — THE TRACKING CONNECTION -->
    <h2>Why You Can't Fix What You Can't Measure</h2>

    <p>Here's the pattern I've seen repeatedly: a man trains consistently, eats "pretty well," and accepts lingering soreness as the price of being over 40. He's not dramatically under-eating protein — he's just 40–50g short of his target most days. Not enough to feel obviously wrong. Enough to slow his recovery by a full day or two.</p>

    <p>The only way to know whether you're hitting your recovery-supporting protein target is to track it. Not forever — but long enough to calibrate your eating patterns to your number. Most men who start tracking discover within a week exactly where their deficit lives. Usually it's breakfast and the post-workout meal. Fix those two, and the 3-day soreness problem often resolves within a few weeks.</p>

    <p>If you're consistently sore for 3+ days after moderate training, the most useful thing you can do before changing your workout, buying supplements, or scaling back your training is to track your protein for 7 days. The data almost always tells you everything you need to know. See <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/is-100g-protein-enough-200lb-man/">whether your current intake is actually enough</a> for your bodyweight.</p>

