      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why am I sore for 3 days after a workout after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Extended soreness after 40 is often a protein problem, not just an age problem. Exercise creates micro-tears in muscle fibers that require adequate protein — specifically enough leucine per meal to trigger muscle protein synthesis — to repair efficiently. When daily protein intake is below 1.2g per kilogram of bodyweight, repair slows, inflammatory byproducts linger, and soreness extends from the normal 24–48 hours to 3+ days.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does protein help with muscle soreness after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — significantly. Protein provides the amino acids required for muscle fiber repair after exercise. Research shows adequate protein intake (1.2–1.6g per kg of bodyweight daily) reduces the duration and severity of delayed onset muscle soreness by accelerating the repair process. Men over 40 are particularly responsive because anabolic resistance means the repair signal is already weaker — adequate protein compensates for that decline.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS)?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Delayed onset muscle soreness is the muscle pain and stiffness that develops 12–48 hours after exercise, caused by microscopic damage to muscle fibers and the resulting inflammatory response during repair. It's a normal part of the adaptation process, but its duration and severity are significantly influenced by protein availability — men with adequate protein intake typically resolve DOMS faster than those running a protein deficit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein do I need to recover faster from workouts after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research supports 1.2–1.6g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight daily to support muscle repair and reduce recovery time. For a 180-pound man (82kg), that's 98–131g per day. Timing matters too — 30–40g of protein within 1–2 hours post-workout provides amino acids when muscle repair demand is highest. Missing this window consistently is one of the most common and correctable recovery mistakes men over 40 make.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
